US Motor Vehicle Fatalities - How Vehicle Age & Model Year Relates to Fatalities

Research Question
This analysis on 2012 - 2015 data examines how the age of the vehicle at the time of the crash and the vehicle’s model year are correlated with the injury outcome of the driver of a passenger vehicle involved in a fatal crash.  This project intends to replicate an earlier study conducted on 2008 - 2011 data to determine if the findings are still valid.

Step 1: Load data, and run numerical and graphical summeries

The Dataset

The accident data in this analysis was loaded via .cvs (2015) and .dta (2012-2014) formatted data files by (accident) year. The data for each year consists of 3 files; Person, Vehicle and Accident.

The Vehicle data file contains information describing in-transport motor vehicles and drivers who are involved in a fatal crash. There is one record per in-transport motor vehicle.

The Person data file contains information describing all persons involved in the crash including motorists (i.e., drivers and passengers of in-transport motor vehicles) and non-motorists (e.g., pedestrians and pedalcyclists). It provides information such as age, vehicle occupant restraint use, and injury severity. There is one record per person.

The Accident data file contains information about crash characteristics and environmental conditions at the time of the crash. There is one record per crash. Fatal crashes only

ST_CASE is the unique case number assigned to each crash. It appears on each data file and is used to merge information from the data files together.

VEH_NO identifies the “Vehicle Number”.  Each vehicle in an accident is assigned a unique number.  ST_CASE and VEH_NO are the unique identifiers for each record and are used to merge the Vehicle File with the Person file.

YEAR records the year in which the crash occurred and is used to merge files from the same year.
Identify Differences Between Years
In order to combine all yearly files into 1 master file, it is necessary to ensure all files have the same variables.
setdiff(acc2013,acc2012)
## [1] "a_ped_f"   "a_pedal_f"

Inner Join

An inner join will be used to merge the person, vehicle and accident files.  This will return all rows from the vehicle file where there are matching values in the person and accident files and all columns from all three files will be returned.  Where there are multiple vehicles per accident case number, all combination of the matches will be returned.
#MERGE FILES
m_perveh_2015<-inner_join(v_veh_2015,v_per_2015, by=c("ST_CASE","YEAR","VEH_NO"))
m_perveh_2014<-inner_join(v_veh_2014,v_per_2014, by=c("st_case","year","veh_no"))
m_perveh_2013<-inner_join(v_veh_2013,v_per_2013, by=c("st_case","year","veh_no"))

Vehicle Age

In this study, the year of the accident and the model year of the vehicle is known. We use this information to calculate the vehicle’s age at the time of the accident. Vehicle Age (V.AGE) = year (YEAR) - model year (A_MOD_YR)

The age of a vehicle is measured by subtracting the vehicle model year from the calendar year at the time of the crash. For example, a 2001 MY vehicle that crashed in 2009 was age 8 at the time of the crash. A vehicle whose age was calculated to be negative one, such as a 2012 MY vehicle crashing in late 2011, was recoded to be age zero. 
fatal$V.AGE<-fatal$YEAR-fatal$A_MOD_YR 
table(fatal$V.AGE)
